    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-30T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-30T16:00:00-05:00" n="894"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d894">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751.67/261: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-30T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 30, 1939—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 30—6:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1031. Bonnet<note n="10" xml:id="d894fn10">Georges Bonnet, French Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> said to me today that the negotiations between
                    France and Turkey had now reached the final phase and he was confident that the
                    treaty with regard to the Hatay would be signed before the end of this week. At
                    the same time the French and Turkish Governments would make a declaration
                    similar to the Anglo-Turkish declaration of May 12th.<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d894fn11">The declaration is contained in statement given by the
                        British Prime Minister, Neville Chamberlain, in the House of Commons, May
                        12, 1939, <hi rend="italic">Parliamentary Debates</hi>, House of Commons,
                        5th ser., vol. 347, p. 952.</note> This declaration would have the binding
                    effect of a formal oral alliance. The British and French Governments would then
                    negotiate with Turkey formal written alliances.</p>
                <p>Rochat<note n="12" xml:id="d894fn12">Charles Rochat, Deputy Director of the
                        Department of Political and Commercial Affairs of the French Ministry for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> said to Wilson<note n="13" xml:id="d894fn13">Edwin
                        C. Wilson, Counselor of Embassy in France.</note> this afternoon in strict
                    confidence that cession of the Hatay probably would become effective on July
                    15th.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
